While I don't set resolutions, I like to look back at the past year to see the lessons I learned through observations and experiences.

My 2022 learnings:
1 - If you are lucky to have a good family, show them you love them. Call them. Spend actual time with them. See your parents for dinner. Call your siblings. Our time on this earth is limited and sacred. Make sure you spend it with people who make you feel like sunshine.
2 - Take care of your body. Stop drinking so much alcohol. Drink water and use sunscreen. And if you have time to look at social media every day, you have time for fitness every day.
3 - Spend time with your pets. You have a life outside of them, but to your pets, you are their entire world. Give them lots of love.
4 - Not everyone in the world is good. Some people are more deceitful than others, and some people are truly evil. If you have any of those types of people around you, try and keep them as far from your energy as you can. Karma will take care of them. I promise you.
5 - You don't have to prove your point to everyone who disagrees with you. Not everyone needs to think the same way or have the same viewpoint. 
6 - You don't need to be available to everyone. You don't have to answer every message you get. You don't have to be available to communicate with people you don't want to communicate with. The block feature is a wonderful one, use it.
7 - Be happy for your friends and encourage their growth. Celebrate their accomplishments, and tell them if they have hurt you. Communicate and you will get through anything in any relationship that matters to you.
8 - Don't hold onto anger. It will show in your eyes and in your face. Let it go.
9 - Remember that everyone has their own struggles. If that person in front of you is driving too slow, maybe their mind is somewhere else. Maybe they are thinking of how they'll afford their rent this month. Always give grace to others.
10. Your children might have a therapist one day. Don't contribute to the things they will need to work through as an adult.
11. Love all, but maintain healthy boundaries.

Love you all! Happy 2023!

I saw a tweet today that really made me think (swipe to see it)

I’m an observer. I always watch human behavior to get a better sense of what someone is really like. If you quiet your mind and watch actions, you can learn a lot. And one of the things I have seen as I get older, is a bitterness that starts to manifest in the 30s and 40s in people who are clearly not happy with their lives.

I feel pretty content with my life. I’m blessed to have a loving husband and stepson, and parents who gave me the world growing up, and are still my biggest cheerleaders. My brother is literally my best friend, and I have a group of girlfriends who are so fierce and amazing, that they drive me to want to do better and be better every day of my life.

But I also didn’t just fall into this life. I built it according to the blueprints I have dreamt about since I was a child. And I think that’s the advice I would give to people in their 20s. Build the life you want. Don’t stay stagnant. For me, success means that my life is different and better than it was years ago. It was good then, but I’m always striving to keep building and never staying in the same place.

Maybe this is why I think tradition is boring. My life is something that constantly evolves, and that keeps me engaged and living with purpose and it keeps me happy. Stagnancy and sticking with the status quo is the root of bitterness. What can you do today to move your life to a different place? How can you keep growing? Sending you all love ❤️

I saw a few of my girlfriends (@namastaywithtay @isarahmz) posting this image today that really resonated with me. Sometimes, you are in fact the asshole in a situation. Sometimes you are the toxic one, and sometimes you are the one who is causing or dredging back an issue that should have been put to bed a long time ago. 

None of us are perfect. And while I try my hardest to extend grace to others, sometimes I suck at it. And it's no secret that the past few years have been extraordinarily difficult for us, We have faced isolation, fear, divisiveness, and are witnessing tragedy after tragedy after tragedy. What harm that must do to our minds and morale. So while I know I am certainly not always wrong (I'd like to think I'm right moooost of the time), sometimes I am not. Sometimes I am, in fact, the asshole.

I had the most wonderful experience meeting with some of the team at Ally Global today. This amazing organization helps survivors of human trafficking find healing and restoration through safe homes, education and job training. Survivors of human trafficking have lived through immense trauma and their pain can make them feel broken and terrified.

Safe homes provide a secure place for children to work through past trauma, build meaningful relationships with others and start to dream for their future.

I'm excited to start volunteering my time with this impactful group. This cause is so, so important to me and close to my heart. Watch this space to learn more about how you can get involved.

When I saw my good friend @kimevans30 post something similar a while back, I knew I wanted to do something similar with my family.

Last week I took my family (minus Truffles because he prefers to stay home) to a delicious French restaurant so we could create our family values. The document you see here is the result of all our thoughts and hopes for how we function as members of our family. Sometimes we get so caught up in just “existing” that we don’t take the time to be conscious about how we exist as members of a family unit.

Creating this document gave us all the space to do just that. Here are our family values. I hope this inspires some of you to do the same. How can you give your family space to determine what is important to you all as individuals and as a family unit?

I feel that so many of us have had such a transformational time in our lives since the spring. We have really gotten a clearer vision for who we are, and who we want to be as the remnants of the pandemic have died down and brought more normalcy to our lives. I think this clarity has also resulted in so many of us editing the who and what belongs in our life. I think so many of us have really raised standards for those who have access to us and our lives, and have edited out toxicity, energy vampires, and those who just don't serve our purpose anymore. 

And for some, we may have entered our "villain" era. And I don't mean that we have become the bad people in the world, but that we have really decreased our tolerance for what we allow in our life, and what energy we choose to have. Life is about so much more than posting inspirational quotes. It's about actually being inspirational. And life is so much more than just paying lip service to our life progressing, but also actually experiencing REAL progress in our personal and professional lives.

And life is so much more than just gathering with people to gossip. If there's one thing I've learned, if they're talking to you about them, trust that they are also talking to them about you.

Keep your standards for your life high and extend these standards to the people you allow in your life. Edit constantly. And protect yourself from people. If you feel something about someone, it's probably correct. Intuition is one of your most powerful tools.

Love you all 🥰

Last month, my husband surprised me with a Peloton Plus as an addition to our home gym. And as someone who absolutely HATES cardio, I wasn't as excited as I really should have been. 

Daily fitness is an important part of my life, but I was also the kind of person who grumbled through my daily cardio before my strength training or pilates. But OMG, this machine is amazing. And this completely is not an ad for Peloton. I am actually excited to clip in my shoes every day, and have only missed two days since the bike entered my home.

So I guess the point of this post is that with the right tools, anything is possible. This bike has changed me into a spin addict. It's like having a personal instructor in my home that I don't want to disappoint lol. Satisfying sweat and a satisfying workout. I'm truly in love...with the husband and the bike 😍.

As I reflect back upon 2023, I would like to share a part of my work with you. I had the pleasure of working with a resilient, beautiful and mighty group of women from the Kaska territory in the Yukon to help plan traditional potlatches to honor the memory of murdered and missing Indigenous women, girls, and 2SLGBTQ individuals in the Kaska community. 

While I wasn't able to travel up to the Yukon to witness these amazing events, I had the honor of helping to plan and measure impact.

The potlatches in September 2023 commenced with the reading of 16 names of Kaska women who had been killed or gone missing over the years. These names represent just a fraction of the more than 4,000 Indigenous women, girls, and two-spirited people across Canada who have experienced similar tragedies.

These gatherings provided a platform for healing, remembrance, and cultural preservation, leaving a lasting impact on participants and the broader community. While there is still much work to be done to address the root causes of this violence, these potlatches served as a beacon of hope and resilience, demonstrating the strength of Indigenous communities in their pursuit of justice and healing.

Thank you to my Kaska aunties and sisters for allowing me to be a part of your journey and your story.

If you would like to learn more, I would direct you all to the CBC podcast: Someone Knows Something. It is the story of Angel Carlick, an 18 year old Kaska citizen, originally from Dease Lake, who worked with the Youth of Today Society. She was set to graduate from high school in May of 2007, but then she disappeared. About six months later, her remains were found at Pilot Mountain, north of Whitehorse. The case is still unsolved.

In true social media trend fashion, here are my ins and outs for 2024🥰🙏. 

In:
-Family is everything. Love your family, hold them close, and spend time with your parents. The relationship you have with your family (especially your parents) will set the tone for all of your relationships. 
-Female friendships. Harvest true friendships and take pride in long standing friendships with strong women. Surround yourself with achievers, not enviers. 
-A strong work ethic and being able to carry yourself with pride in knowing that you can take care of yourself financially and emotionally. 
-Hustle. And know how to do your job. Take pride in your work, and only work with people who know how to do their jobs. I've wasted far too much money and time on "professional" duds. Learn from my mistakes.
-Have a savings account, invest wisely, and have assets.
-Have a workout schedule and move your body every day.
-Drink water
-Mocktails
-Volunteering. If you have hours to spend on tik tok, you have hours to help your community.

Out
-Darkness and negative energy in your life. And this could be in the form of work, relationships or friendships. You are a reflection of those you keep around you, edit often.
-Mending every broken relationship. I truly believe that God removes people from your life who He sees through. Let Him do his work. 
-Alcohol
-Gossip. It's not cute anymore. 
🙏❤️

Embracing the journey of aging has been a revelation. My 40s have taught me that it's not the passage of time we should fear, but rather the choices we make along the way. These years offer a window into the impact of our earlier decisions on our later selves. Opting for a healthy lifestyle, staying serene, hydrating, ditching alcohol, and cultivating a love for fitness are all investments that pay dividends as we 'age'. Remember, it's not the number on your ID that counts, but how you feel and the joy you find in your reflection. Happy Sunday, loves!
